  This rule allows the detection of such uses, which often occur because the logical operators
  (<code>&amp;&amp;</code>, <code>||</code> and <code>!</code>) can be easily confused with the bitwise operators
  (<code>&amp;</code>, <code>|</code> and <code>~</code>).
</p>

<h2>Noncompliant Code Example</h2>
<pre>
bool b1 = true;
bool b2 = false;
int8_t s8a;
if ( b1 &amp; b2 ) // Noncompliant
if ( ~b1 ) // Noncompliant
if ( b1 &lt; b2 ) // Noncompliant
if ( b1 ^ b2 ) // Noncompliant
</pre>

<h2>Compliant Solution</h2>
<pre>
if ( b1 &amp;&amp; b2 )
if ( !b1 )
if ( b1 == false )
if ( b1 == b2 )
if ( b1 != b2 )
s8a = b1 ? 3 : 7;
</pre>

<h2>See</h2>
<ul>
  <li>MISRA C++:2008, 4-5-1 - Expressions with type bool shall not be used as operands to built-in operators other than the assignment operator =, the logical operators &amp;&amp;, ||, !, the equality operators == and !=, the unary &amp; operator, and the conditional operator.</li>
</ul>
