cobolCOBOL.RedefineUsageCheckAvoid using "REDEFINES" clause"MINOR*cobol2COBOL.RedefineUsageCheck:É	<p>Use of REDEFINES clause introduces type safety and portability risks, and as such their usage should be avoided where possible\n</p>
<p>Redefines have traditionally been used to primarily solve 2 types problems: </p>

<ul>
  <li>1. Redefines are sometimes used to conserve memory or disk space by compacting many different data types into the same physical data block. 
Memory and disk size limitations are no longer a key concern and this reduces the priority of this type of optimisation. 
Where space optimisation is still relevant, normalisation of data schemas should be considered</li>

  <li>2. Redefines are sometimes used as a quick way of reinterpretting data. 
A good example would be a date which can be interpretted as a single string, or separate day-month-year components. 
In high-performance areas this will give the fastest reformatting, though where performance is not a concern, 
a more explicit function gives better long term flexibility. For instance, 
if a future change required one of the elements to become variable length rather than fixed length, 
the redefine approach would not be able to accomodate the change</li>
</ul>
