cobolS1732C"FOR READ ONLY" or "FOR UPDATE" should be specified for DB2 cursors"CRITICAL*cobol2S1732:÷<p>Explicitly defining a cursor as read-only can improve performance by avoiding table locking. This allows other SQL requests to execute in parallel. Therefore when a cursor will only be used to read data, without modifying anything, the <code>FOR READ ONLY</code> clause or its synonyn, <code>FOR FETCH ONLY</code>, should be used.</p>
<p>Conversely when a cursor will modify data, that too should be specified using the <code>FOR UPDATE</code> clause. </p>
<p>In short, it's better to always explicitly define the purpose of the cursor with help of the <code>FOR READ ONLY</code>, <code>FOR FETCH ONLY</code> or <code>FOR UPDATE</code> clauses.</p>
<h2>Noncompliant Code Example</h2>

<pre>
EXEC SQL DECLARE CMAJ_0A CURSOR
  FOR SELECT C_BQ,
    FROM       S1ORDCOU
    WHERE C_BQ = :TORD-C-BQ
END-EXEC
</pre>
<h2>Compliant Solution</h2>

<pre>
EXEC SQL DECLARE CMAJ_0A CURSOR
  FOR SELECT C_BQ,
    FROM       S1ORDCOU
    WHERE C_BQ = :TORD-C-BQ
  FOR READ ONLY
END-EXEC
</pre>
