objcS2757'"=+" should not be used instead of "+=""CRITICAL*objc2S2757:è<p>
  The use of operators pairs (<code>=+</code>) where the reversed,
  single operator was meant (<code>+=</code>) will compile and run,
  but not produce the expected results.</p>
<p>
  This rule raises an issue when <code>=+</code>, <code>=-</code>, <code>=!</code>, <code>=&amp;</code>, <code>=*</code>, <code>+=+</code>,  and <code>-=-</code> are used,
  but ignores the operators when they're spaced out: <code>= +</code>, <code>= -</code>, <code>= !</code>, <code>= &amp;</code>, <code>= *</code>, <code>+= +</code>, <code>-= -</code>.
</p>

<h2>Noncompliant Code Example</h2>
<pre>
int target = -5;
int num = 3;

target =- num;  // Noncompliant; target = -3. Is that really what's meant?
target =+ num; // Noncompliant; target = 3
</pre>

<h2>Compliant Solution</h2>
<pre>
int target = -5;
int num = 3;

target = -num;  // Compliant; intent to assign inverse value of num is clear
target += num;
</pre>
